        <p><strong>Borland Sidekick</strong> was an early personal information manager (PIM) that {'Borland'|link_urls:'/c'} launched in 1984 under <strong>Philippe Kahn</strong>'s leadership.</p>
        <p>It was an early and popular <strong>terminate and stay resident program (TSR)</strong> program for {'DOS'|link_urls:'i'} operating systems, which enabled computer users activate the program using a hot key combination (by default <code>Ctrl-Alt</code>) while working in other programs.</p>
        <p>Although a text mode program, Sidekick's window-based interface echoed that of the {'Apple Macitosh'|link_urls:'i'} and anticipated the eventual look of Microsoft {'Windows 2'|link_urls:'i'}.</p>
        <p>It included a personal calendar, text editor (with {'WordStar'|link_urls:'i'} like command interface), calculator, ASCII chart, address book, and phone dialer.</p>
        <p>According to the prospectus for Borland's initial public offering of stock to the public, Sidekick sold more than 1 million copies in its first three years.</p>
